#Text=struga :   A corridor formed along a bedding plane in karst country.
#Text=subjacent karst :  Karst landscape in noncarbonate rocks due to presence of karstified rocks beneath the surface formation.
#Text=submarine spring :  Large offshore emergence, generally from cavernous limestone, but in some areas from beds of lava.
#Text=subsidence :  Lowering of the surface of the ground because of removal of support. Caused in karst areas by subterranean solution or collapse of caves.
#Text=subterranean river :  Underground stream of flowing water, not necessarily large.
#Text=sump :  A pool of underground water or point on an underground stream that has a submerged extension, the nature of which has not been determined.

#Text=swallet, swallow hole :   A place where water disappears urderground in a limestone region. A swallow hole generally implies water loss in a closed depression or blind valley, whereas a swallet may refer to water loss into alluvium at a streambed, even though there is no depression.
#Text=syngenetic karst :  Karst developed in eolian calcarenite where lithification of dune sands and productior of karst phenomena occurred simultaneously.
#Text=terraced flowstone :  Shallow rimstone pools on outward-sloping walls.
#Text=threshold :  That part of a cave system to which light penetrates in some degree.
#Text=through cave :  Cave through which a stream runs from entrance to exit or formerly did so. Synonym:  Durchgangshohle.
#Text=torca :   Large closed depression, more or less circular; a doline.

#Text=torricellian chamber :  A submerged airfilled chamber of a cave at a pressure below atmospheric pressure, sealed by water, having an air-water surface above that of adjacent free air-water surfaces.
#Text=tourelle :   A little tower; applied to small flat-topped buttes of limestone in karst areas. Contrasted with pitons, which have pointed tops, and with coupoles, which have rounded tops.

#Text=tower karst, Turmkarst :  Karst topography characterized by isolated limestone hills separated by areas of alluvium or other detrital sand; towers are generally steep-sided forest-covered hills, and many have flat tops.
